# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gcp-cloud-scheduler
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The daemon name originates from Chronos, the Greek word for time.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] `cron` is generally available on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The actions of cron are driven by a *crontab* (cron table) file.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The crontab files are stored where the lists of jobs and other instructions to the cron daemon are kept.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Users can have their own individual crontab files and often there is a system-wide crontab file (usually in `/etc` or a subdirectory of `/etc` e.g.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] `/etc/cron.d`) that only system administrators can edit.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The syntax of each line expects a cron expression made of five fields which represent the time to execute the command, followed by a shell command to execute.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] While normally the job is executed when the time/date specification fields all match the current time and date, there is one exception: if both "day of month" (field 3) and "day of week" (field 5) are restricted (do not contain "*"), then one or both must match the current day.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This example runs a shell program called export_dump.sh at 23:45 (11:45 PM) every Saturday.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Note: On some systems it is also possible to specify `*/n` to run for every *n*-th interval of time.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Also, specifying multiple specific time intervals can be done with commas (e.g., `1,2,3`).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The line below would output "hello world" to the command line every 5th minute of every first, second and third hour (i.e., 01:00, 01:05, 01:10, up until 03:55).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The configuration file for a user can be edited by calling `crontab -e` regardless of where the actual implementation stores this file.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Some `cron` implementations, such as the popular 4th BSD edition written by Paul Vixie and included in many Linux distributions, add a sixth field: an account username that runs the specified job (subject to user existence and permissions).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This is allowed only in the system crontabs—not in others, which are each assigned to a single user to configure.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The sixth field is alternatively sometimes used for *year* instead of an account username—the nncron daemon for Windows does this.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The Amazon EventBridge implementation of cron does not use 0 based day of week, instead it is 1-7 SUN-SAT (instead of 0-6), as well as supporting additional expression features such as first-weekday and last-day-of-month.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] `@reboot` configures a job to run once when the daemon is started.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Since cron is typically never restarted, this typically corresponds to the machine being booted.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This behavior is enforced in some variations of cron, such as that provided in Debian, so that simply restarting the daemon does not re-run `@reboot` jobs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] `@reboot` can be useful if there is a need to start up a server or daemon under a particular user, and the user does not have access to configure init to start the program.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Note that if neither of these files exists then, depending on site-dependent configuration parameters, either only the super user can use cron jobs, or all users can use cron jobs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Most cron implementations simply interpret crontab entries in the system time zone setting that the cron daemon runs under.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This can be a source of dispute if a large multi-user machine has users in several time zones, especially if the system default time zone includes the potentially confusing DST.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Thus, a cron implementation may as a special case recognize lines of the form "CRON_TZ=<time zone>" in user crontabs, interpreting subsequent crontab entries relative to that time zone.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The cron in Version 7 Unix was a system service (later called a daemon) invoked from `/etc/rc` when the operating system entered multi-user mode.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Determine if any commands must run at the current date and time, and if so, run them as the superuser, root.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This version of cron was basic and robust but it also consumed resources whether it found any work to do or not.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In an experiment at Purdue University in the late 1970s to extend cron's service to all 100 users on a time-shared VAX, it was found to place too much load on the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The next version of cron, with the release of Unix System V, was created to extend the capabilities of cron to all users of a Unix system, not just the superuser.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Though this may seem trivial today with most Unix and Unix-like systems having powerful processors and small numbers of users, at the time it required a new approach on a one-MIPS system having roughly 100 user accounts.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In the August, 1977 issue of the *Communications of the ACM*, W.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] A Purdue graduate student, Robert Brown, reviewing this article, recognized the parallel between cron and discrete event simulators, and created an implementation of the Franta–Maly event list manager (ELM) for experimentation.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Discrete event simulators run in *virtual time*, peeling events off the event queue as quickly as possible and advancing their notion of "now" to the scheduled time of the next event.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Running the event simulator in "real time" instead of virtual time created a version of cron that spent most of its time sleeping, waiting for the scheduled time to execute the task at the head of the event list.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The following school year brought new students into the graduate program at Purdue, including Keith Williamson, who joined the systems staff in the Computer Science department.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] As a "warm up task" Brown asked him to flesh out the prototype cron into a production service, and this multi-user cron went into use at Purdue in late 1979.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This version of cron wholly replaced the `/etc/cron` that was in use on the computer science department's VAX 11/780 running 32/V.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] For each crontab file found, determine the next time in the future that each command must run.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Place those commands on the Franta–Maly event list with their corresponding time and their "five field" time specifier.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] On awakening and after verifying the correct time, execute the task at the head of the queue (in background) with the privileges of the user who created it.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Determine the next time in the future to run this command and place it back on the event list at that time value.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Additionally, the daemon responds to SIGHUP signals to rescan modified crontab files and schedules special "wake up events" on the hour and half-hour to look for modified crontab files.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Much detail is omitted here concerning the inaccuracies of computer time-of-day tracking, Unix alarm scheduling, explicit time-of-day changes, and process management, all of which account for the majority of the lines of code in this cron.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This cron also captured the output of *stdout* and *stderr* and e-mailed any output to the crontab owner.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The resources consumed by this cron scale only with the amount of work it is given and do not inherently increase over time, with the exception of periodically checking for changes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Williamson completed his studies and departed the University with a Masters of Science in Computer Science and joined AT&T Bell Labs in Murray Hill, New Jersey, and took this cron with him.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This version of cron later appeared largely unchanged in Unix System V and in BSD and their derivatives, Solaris from Sun Microsystems, IRIX from Silicon Graphics, HP-UX from Hewlett-Packard, and AIX from IBM.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Technically, the original license for these implementations should be with the Purdue Research Foundation who funded the work, but this took place at a time when little concern was given to such matters.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] With the advent of the GNU Project and Linux, new crons appeared.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The most prevalent of these is the Vixie cron, originally coded by Paul Vixie in 1987.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Version 3 of **Vixie cron** was released in late 1993.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Version 4.1 was renamed to **ISC Cron** and was released in January 2004.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Version 3, with some minor bugfixes, is used in most distributions of Linux and BSDs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In 2007, Red Hat forked vixie-cron 4.1 to the cronie project, adding features such as PAM and SELinux support.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In 2009, anacron 2.3 was merged into cronie.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Anacron is not an independent cron program however; another cron job must call it.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] DragonFly's dcron was made by its founder Matt Dillon, and its maintainership was taken over by Jim Pryor in 2010.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In 2003, Dale Mellor introduced mcron, a cron variant written in Guile which provides cross-compatibility with Vixie cron while also providing greater flexibility as it allows arbitrary scheme code to be used in scheduling calculations and job definitions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Since both the mcron daemon and the crontab files are usually written in scheme (though mcron also accepts traditional Vixie crontabs), the cumulative state of a user's job queue is available to their job code, which may be scheduled to run iff the results of other jobs meet certain criteria.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Mcron is deployed by default under the Guix package manager, which includes provisions (services) for the package manager to monadically emit mcron crontabs while both ensuring that packages needed for job execution are installed and that the corresponding crontabs correctly refer to them.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] A webcron solution schedules ring tasks to run on a regular basis wherever cron implementations are not available in a web hosting environment.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In 2025, the Open Cron Pattern Specification (OCPS) was published to address fragmentation in cron syntax across different implementations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] OCPS 1.0 provides a formal specification of the Vixie cron dialect, codifying the five-field pattern format with explicit rules for previously ambiguous edge cases.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The specification is designed as a backward-compatible superset, with future versions planned to incrementally add features such as predefined schedules, second-level precision, and advanced calendar modifiers while maintaining compatibility with earlier versions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] A cron expression is a string comprising five, six, or seven fields separated by white space that represents a set of times, normally as a schedule to execute some routine.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Comments begin with a comment mark #, and must be on a line by themselves.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The month and weekday abbreviations are not case-sensitive.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In the particular case of the system crontab file (/etc/crontab), a *user* field inserts itself before the *command*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Asterisks (also known as wildcard) represents "all".
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] For example, using "* * * * *" will run every minute.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Using "* * * * 1" will run every minute only on Monday.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Using six asterisks means every second when seconds are supported.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Commas are used to separate items of a list.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] For example, using "MON,WED,FRI" in the 5th field (day of week) means Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] For example, "2000-2010" indicates every year between 2000 and 2010, inclusive.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] % are sent to the command as standard input.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The following are non-standard characters and exist only in some cron implementations, such as the Quartz Java scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In the day-of-month field, it specifies the last day of the month.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The 'W' character is allowed for the day-of-month field.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This character is used to specify the weekday (Monday-Friday) nearest the given day.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] " is specified as the value for the day-of-month field, the meaning is: "the nearest weekday to the 15th of the month." So, if the 15th is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Friday the 14th.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] If the 15th is a Sunday, the trigger fires on Monday the 16th.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] If the 15th is a Tuesday, then it fires on Tuesday the 15th.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] However, if "1W" is specified as the value for day-of-month, and the 1st is a Saturday, the trigger fires on Monday the 3rd, as it does not 'jump' over the boundary of a month's days.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] The 'W' character can be specified only when the day-of-month is a single day, not a range or list of days.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] '#' is allowed for the day-of-week field, and must be followed by a number between one and five.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] It allows specifying constructs such as "the second Friday" of a given month.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] For example, entering "5#3" in the day-of-week field corresponds to the third Friday of every month.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] ' for leaving either day-of-month or day-of-week blank.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] if cron started-up on 8:25am, and would run at this time every day until restarted again.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In vixie-cron, slashes can be combined with ranges to specify step values.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] in the minutes field indicates every 5 minutes (see note below about frequencies).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] POSIX does not define a use for slashes; its rationale (commenting on a BSD extension) notes that the definition is based on System V format but does not exclude the possibility of extensions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Some language-specific libraries offering crontab scheduling ability do not require "strict" ranges 15-59/XX to the left of the slash when ranges are used.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] In these cases, 15/XX is the same as a vixie-cron schedule of 15-59/10 in the minutes section.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] Similarly, one can remove the extra -23 from 0-23/XX, -31 from 1-31/XX, and -12 from 1-12/XX for hours, days, and months; respectively.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] continuous integration system to indicate that a "hashed" value is substituted.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] ' indicates that the task is performed every hour at an unspecified but invariant time for each task.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/cron] This allows spreading out tasks over time, rather than having all of them start at the same time and compete for resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] A **job scheduler** is a computer application for controlling unattended background program execution of jobs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] This is commonly called **batch scheduling**, as execution of non-interactive jobs is often called batch processing, though traditional *job* and *batch* are distinguished and contrasted; see that page for details.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Other synonyms include **batch system**, **distributed resource management system** (**DRMS**), **distributed resource manager** (**DRM**), and, commonly today, **workload automation** (**WLA**).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] The data structure of jobs to run is known as the job queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Modern job schedulers typically provide a graphical user interface and a single point of control for definition and monitoring of background executions in a distributed network of computers.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Increasingly, job schedulers are required to orchestrate the integration of real-time business activities with traditional background IT processing across different operating system platforms and business application environments.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] If software from a completely different area includes all or some of those features, this software can be considered to have job scheduling capabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Most operating systems, such as Unix and Windows, provide basic job scheduling capabilities, notably by at and batch, cron, and the Windows Task Scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Web hosting services provide job scheduling capabilities through a control panel or a webcron solution.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Many programs such as DBMS, backup, ERPs, and BPM also include relevant job-scheduling capabilities.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Operating system ("OS") or point program supplied job-scheduling will not usually provide the ability to schedule beyond a single OS instance or outside the remit of the specific program.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] These advanced capabilities can be written by in-house developers but are more often provided by suppliers who specialize in systems-management software.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] There are many concepts that are central to almost every job scheduler implementation and that are widely recognized with minimal variations: jobs, dependencies, job streams, and users.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Beyond the basic, single OS instance scheduling tools there are two major architectures that exist for Job Scheduling software.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Job schedulers have been one of the major components of IT infrastructure since the early mainframe systems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] At first, stacks of punched cards were processed one after the other, hence the term "batch processing".
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/job-scheduler] Various schemes are used to decide which particular job to run.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A **periodic function** is a function that repeats its values at regular intervals.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] For example, the trigonometric functions, which are used to describe waves and other repeating phenomena, are periodic.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Many aspects of the natural world have periodic behavior, such as the phases of the Moon, the swinging of a pendulum, and the beating of a heart.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The length of the interval over which a periodic function repeats is called its **period**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Any function that is not periodic is called **aperiodic**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A function is defined as **periodic** if its values repeat at regular intervals.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] For example, the positions of the hands on a clock display periodic behavior as they cycle through the same positions every 12 hours.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This repeating interval is known as the **period**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A **nonzero** constant P for which this condition holds is called a **period** of the function.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] If a period P exists, any integer multiple $nP$ (for a positive integer n ) is also a period.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] If there is a *least positive* period, it is called the **fundamental period** (also **primitive period** or **basic period**).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Often, "the" period of a function is used to refer to its fundamental period.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Geometrically, a periodic function's graph exhibits translational symmetry.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Its graph is invariant under translation in the x -direction by a distance of P .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This implies that the entire graph can be formed from copies of one particular portion, repeated at regular intervals.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Periodic behavior can be illustrated through both common, everyday examples and more formal mathematical functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Functions that map real numbers to real numbers can display periodicity, which is often visualized on a graph.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] An example is the function f that represents the "fractional part" of its argument.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The graph of the function f is a sawtooth wave.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The trigonometric functions are common examples of periodic functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The sine function and cosine function are periodic with a fundamental period of $2\pi$ , as illustrated in the figure to the right.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The field of Fourier series investigates the concept that an arbitrary periodic function can be expressed as a sum of trigonometric functions with matching periods.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Some functions are periodic but possess properties that make them less intuitive.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The Dirichlet function, for example, is periodic, with any nonzero rational number serving as a period.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] However, it does not possess a fundamental period.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Functions with a domain in the complex numbers can exhibit more complex periodic properties.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A function on the complex plane can have two distinct, incommensurate periods without being a constant function.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The elliptic functions are a primary example of such functions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Periodic functions can take on values many times.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A significant property related to integration is that if $f(x)$ is an integrable periodic function with period P , then its definite integral over any interval of length P is the same.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This property is crucial in areas such as Fourier series, where the coefficients are determined by integrals over one period.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] If $f(x)$ is a function with period P , then $f(ax)$ , where a is a non-zero real number such that $ax$ is within the domain of f , is periodic with period ${\frac {P}{|a|}}$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A key property of many periodic functions is that they can be described by a Fourier series.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This series represents a periodic function as a sum of simpler periodic functions, namely sines and cosines.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] For example, a sound wave from a musical instrument can be broken down into the fundamental note and various overtones.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This decomposition is a powerful tool in fields like physics and signal processing.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] While most "well-behaved" periodic functions can be represented this way, Fourier series can only be used for periodic functions or for functions defined on a finite length.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] If f is a periodic function with period P that can be described by a Fourier series, the coefficients of the series can be described by an integral over an interval of length P .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Any function that is a combination of periodic functions with the same period is also periodic (though its fundamental period may be smaller).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] The concept of periodicity can be generalized beyond functions on the real number line.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] For example, the idea of a repeating pattern can be applied to shapes in multiple dimensions, such as a periodic tessellation of the plane.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A sequence can also be viewed as a function defined on the natural numbers, and the concept of a periodic sequence is defined accordingly.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] One subset of periodic functions is that of **antiperiodic functions**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] This is a function f such that $f(x+P)=-f(x)$ for all x .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] For example, the sine and cosine functions are $\pi$ -antiperiodic and $2\pi$ -periodic.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] While a P -antiperiodic function is a $2P$ -periodic function, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A further generalization appears in the context of Bloch's theorems and Floquet theory, which govern the solution of various periodic differential equations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] where k is a real or complex number (the *Bloch wavevector* or *Floquet exponent*).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Functions of this form are sometimes called **Bloch-periodic** in this context.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A periodic function is the special case $k=0$ , and an antiperiodic function is the special case $k=\pi /P$ .
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Whenever $kP/\pi$ is rational, the function is also periodic.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] A possible way out is to define a periodic function on a bounded but periodic domain.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] That is, each element in ${\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z} }$ is an equivalence class of real numbers that share the same fractional part.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Thus a function like $f:{\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z} }\to \mathbb {R}$ is a representation of a 1-periodic function.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Consider a real waveform consisting of superimposed frequencies, expressed in a set as ratios to a fundamental frequency, f: F = 1⁄f [f1 f2 f3 ... fN] where all non-zero elements ≥1 and at least one of the elements of the set is 1.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] To find the period, T, first find the least common denominator of all the elements in the set.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Consider that for a simple sinusoid, T = 1⁄f.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] Therefore, the LCD can be seen as a periodicity multiplier.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/periodic-function] If no least common denominator exists, for instance if one of the above elements were irrational, then the wave would not be periodic.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:gcp-cloud-scheduler/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
